# CEO Review — CivicQ Plan (plan-ceo)

I reviewed `planner.out` against `brief`/`intake.out`, the posting, and the
10/10 feature-richness target. This is a strong, disciplined plan. It is faithful
to the brief and ambitious enough for 10/10. Passing it forward.

## What the plan gets right (verified against the posting)

- **Spec fidelity is the spine.** All 10 sections are listed in the client's
  exact order, plus the `/methodology` page. Section structure is preserved
  (2x2 feature grid with status pills, two-column live/in-dev disclosure,
  three-column partners). This directly answers the client's stated fear of a
  dev who "redesigns or rewrites" instead of building to spec.
- **All three data visualizations are real, coded, and accessible** (SVG, no
  third-party embeds, no gray-box placeholders), each with a clear accessibility
  story (ARIA, visually-hidden data-table fallback, label-on-segment instead of
  legend-only, color-blind-safe ramp, no partisan hue coding). This is the
  make-or-break item and the plan treats it as first-class.
- **Email capture is real persistence, not a claim.** `civicq_blueprint.py`
  (modeled on `spotify_blueprint.py`) with `POST /civicq/subscribe` +
  `GET /civicq/csv-export` proves the "Mailchimp/ConvertKit + CSV backup"
  requirement with a working backend. Correct call for 10/10.
- **Nonpartisan discipline is baked into the design system** (teal/gold + neutral
  grays, explicitly no red/blue), which matches the whole CivicQ identity.
- **Every requirement is traced** (Section 9 matrix) and every to-apply ask is
  answered: portfolio = live demo, timeline = 40/40/20 milestone plan within the
  2-4 week window, three-graphics approach = all coded by Michael, fixed bid =
  $4,200 (inside the $3,500-$5,000 range, justifiably mid-to-upper given the full
  build). Good.
- Prototype-vs-full decision is correctly FULL with the fallback triggers
  evaluated, and scope fences are explicit so nothing creeps.

## Notes to carry into the build (not blockers — pass-with-guidance)

These do not require a planner loop; demo-builder should fold them in.

1. **Scoring chart interactivity.** Brief says "interactive/animated preferred."
   Plan currently specifies animated draw-in only. For 10/10, add lightweight
   interactivity (hover/focus to surface each dimension's exact weight, keyboard
   focusable bars) on top of the scroll animation. Keep it reduced-motion-safe.
2. **File-cap pressure is real.** Cramming all 10 sections inline in `Home.jsx`
   to stay at ~11 files is acceptable, but do not let it degrade polish. If a
   couple of extra small section/component files are needed to keep the code
   clean and the sections genuinely production-quality, that is the right
   trade-off — 10/10 polish beats a hard file count. The ~12-file cap is a
   guardrail against bloat, not a reason to ship cramped markup.
3. **Lighthouse 85+ mobile is graded.** Self-host or `font-display: swap` the
   Newsreader/Inter fonts, lazy-load the hero video poster, and keep JS lean so
   the perf number is actually hit, not just asserted. deploy-test should report
   the real score.
4. **Analytics stub is fine** per scope fences, but make the event hooks visibly
   real in the demo (console-logged custom events on CTA + form submit) so the
   "analytics installed" requirement has on-screen evidence, with the Plausible
   site-id swap documented.
5. **Org Hub mockup** must read as an intentional product shot (browser chrome +
   mock dashboard), not a wireframe gray box — the plan says this; hold the build
   to it at QA.

## Decision

The plan is ambitious enough for 10/10, faithful to the brief, correctly scoped,
and fully traceable. No requirements were missed (no REDIRECT to intake needed),
and it is sharp enough that a planner loop would add cost without changing the
outcome. The notes above are build-time guidance for demo-builder and the
post-build CEO check, not plan defects.

VERDICT: pass
